While you might have your heart set on spending your next four years pretending to be Harry Potter at Princeton’s beautiful campus, it’s important to look at the data. With acceptance rates under 10% for all of these example schools, it would be ill-advised to put all of your acceptance eggs into one basket.

&nbsp;

Furthermore, just because one top college sends you a letter turning you down, it definitely doesn’t mean others will. Each year, the top colleges have to make incredibly difficult decisions. A very large percentage (much higher than 8%) of the 18,000 applicants to MIT would do well at the institute if they were accepted. But due to the huge volume of applicants, the MIT admissions officers have the task to build a class out of a huge number of qualified candidates, while also turning down equally qualified candidates.

&nbsp;

Here’s the tough truth:

&nbsp;
<h3>Getting into a top college involves a lot of luck.</h3>
&nbsp;

It sucks, but that’s the way the system works right now. The great news is that there are a lot of amazing colleges. Even though it’s a lot of work, my advice is simple:

&nbsp;
<h3>Apply to as many as you can!</h3>
&nbsp;

What better way to increase your luck than to put more tickets in the raffle? Here’s a reproduction of my college plan, and I would highly suggest that you come up with something similar.

