At the time when I received my acceptance letter from MIT, I had applications for all of my “reach schools” ready to send in. I had also been preparing to fill out the applications for my “secondary schools.” AND I had already been accepted (verbally or officially) to Texas A&amp;M, Stevens Institute of Technology, and Colorado School of Mines.

&nbsp;
<h3>I was fully ready to get rejected by MIT.</h3>
&nbsp;

And if I had been rejected, I would have been bummed of course, but I simply would have simply gone forward with my plan. Something was going to work out, and I was going to have a great college experience.

&nbsp;

This is why while I advocate having a dream school, realize that it’s not the only school that you will love. Don’t hold on too tightly to the idea, as your other applications will begin to lose their potency. As many amazing memories as I have at MIT, I’m sure that if I’d gone to any of the other schools on my list, I’d have equally great ones.
<blockquote>“Trust your luck, Taran Wanderer. But don't forget to put out your nets!”
― Lloyd Alexander, Taran Wanderer</blockquote>
Be aggressive in your college search. Be flexible, open minded, and cast a wide net.

